move.commentAfter: An idea of Victor Bologan's, who documented his expertise in this opening in his book The Chebanenko Slav.
This aggressive looking move will mainly provoke Black's aggression. Here and on the previous move, sacrificing the knight on c6 was an interesting possibility.
White's attacking chances are hard to detect. Now Eljanov jumps at the opportunity to sacrifice a piece for a couple of pawns and a fairly risk-free initiative.
An unfortunate idea that leads to a premature end of the game. He should have surrendered a third pawn with
White's position is difficult but not hopeless.
A weak move, which speeds up the end.
The Chebanenko pawn has moved from a6 to a3 to deal the final blow. White resigned.
